into their system. However it will work with anything that speaks HTTP(S) and run on any platform that ASP.NET Core supports." style="text;html=1;align=left;verticalAlign=top;spacingTop=-4;fontSize=14;labelBackgroundColor=none;whiteSpace=wrap;" vertex="1" parent="1"> <mxGeometry x="828.5" y="96.5" width="450" height="115" as="geometry" /> </mxCell> <mxCell id="LBuo2vKL3A2V7EPNbGfz-13" value="Atlanta is the core microservice. It uses event-driven architecture. Implementing CQRS in your application can maximize its performance, scalability, and security. Data is stored in the MySQL relational database, and data is retrieved through a DynamoDB non-relational database. To synchronize data between the relational database and the non-relational database, the SQS message broker is used." style="text;html=1;align=left;verticalAlign=top;spacingTop=-4;fontSize=14;labelBackgroundColor=none;whiteSpace=wrap;" vertex="1" parent="1"> <mxGeometry x="828.5" y="175.5" width="450" height="117" as="geometry" /> </mxCell> <mxCell id="LBuo2vKL3A2V7EPNbGfz-14" value="MySQL relational database. div.div: Ocelot is aimed at people using .NET running a microservices / service-oriented architecture that need a unified point of entry into their system. However it will work with anything that speaks HTTP(S) and run on any platform that ASP.NET Core supports.

div.div: Atlanta is the core microservice. It uses event-driven architecture. Implementing CQRS in your application can maximize its performance, scalability, and security. Data is stored in the MySQL relational database, and data is retrieved through a DynamoDB non-relational database. To synchronize data between the relational database and the non-relational database, the SQS message broker is used.
